EXTENSIONS:
-----------

The maximum number of "Bonhommes" is limited only by the available RAM when
loading BCS... And your imagination!
Yes, you can easily add, replace or modify some "bonhommes" as you wish it.
To do it, simply use a drawing tool (like DPaint for example) and take an
existing "bonhomme" as reference.
To succeed, you will have to create 3 brushes with respect of the original
sizes and respect my naming rules:

tetX.br    <- For the head        X design the Xth "bonhomme"
corX.br    <- For the body        If there is already 7 "bonhommes", the
basX.br    <- For the legs        new one will have X equal to 8.

Be sure to save your work in "Reference_unit:BCS/BCS_BR" otherwise BCS will
not take them in count when loading.
You can also copy it in RAM:BCS/BCS_BR to directly test it when using BCS.
I hope that you have enough RAM in this case!  :-)

For information, 5 "bonhommes" request aproximately 160K of RAM and every
new one needs around 17K RAM more. With a little luck, BCS should run on
a 512K RAM Amiga...

There are some sounds included in BCS_SON. You can put your own IFF sounds
instead of mine (or remove it) to suit your needs. To use them, you must
preserve the names that I used...


CONCLUSION:
-----------
I developped this little program for my daughter when she was 3 years old
because I wasn't able to find software reaching the following needs:
- Familiarize a 3 years old kid with a computer
- Use a mouse in a simple logic environment
- Little fun to keep the children interrest
- Way to avoid boring the children with surprises (New "bonhommes")

When I achieved it, I found that it was also a good memory exercice
combined with a logic approach.

Looking how both my children react to BCS, I feel it is a success. I hope
that many other children will also enjoy it! If it is the case, please,
make me a favour: Send me a postcard to tell me. Fair deal, isn't it?

